title: Sturdy Accessory Holder for Dyson V6 V7 V8

description.text:
Sturdy accessory holder for Dyson V6, V7, and V8 vacuums (and possibly others). With some good wall anchors, this will hold even the big motorized vacuum heads.

Works just like the factory dual accessory holder that's built into the charging station - snap in your accessories from underneath, and release it just like you were removing the tool from the vacuum. The intended mounting position is flat side up, with the two side mounting holes above the single center mounting hole.

Designed to be friendly to FDM printers:

  • Integrated custom supports for holes (snaps out with minor cleanup - no slicer supports needed)
  • All big overhangs are less than 20 degrees off vertical
  • Only a few small chamfers that result in a few layers of 45 degree overhangs
  • Large surface touching the bed for better bed adhesion

This design was inspired by @Cornick's Dyson Attachment Storage design (which unfortunately didn't fit my attachments), so I've flagged this as a remix.

description.text:
Edit/update: Thanks to everyone who has added it to additional groups/collections. I have reprinted it in blue so as to take a photograph with better contrast than the original red on orange.

While learning to print with flexible filament on my Prusa i3 Mk2s, I wanted to be able to quickly and repeatably set the spring tension on the extruder feed bearing. This gauge will probably be usable on many other models of printer with a similar tension mechanism. (springs on M3 screws).

Loose and tight versions

Both versions of the gauge include 12.0mm and 12.5mm settings. As a longer tool is awkward to position, I created two shorter tools, one for looser tension settings and one to go tighter.

The Loose version includes larger sizes up to 16mm at which point my printer does not compress the spring at all until filament is loaded. This is the version you'd want for printing flexible filament that wants a very low tension.

The tight version extends down to 9.5mm at which point my springs have completely compressed; this is probably uselessly tight. I don't have any filaments that require more tension than standard, so I've included this just for the sake of completeness. (I'm curious if there are materials which require a lot of tension?)

Using the gauge

  1. loosen each bolt a bit looser than you want
  2. place the section of the tool marked with the desired width over the spring
  3. tighten the bolt until both washers make gentle contact with the gauge.

The total distance between the extruder housing and the head of the bolt will be a bit greater (the thickness of two washers), so I have been using the 12.0mm or 12.5mm marks as "normal" for the recommended 13mm.

I usually try to get the flat edge of the gauge against the extruder housing to help ensure the gauge isn't skewed.

Notes:

I reduced the first layer to 0.15 -- matching the layer height -- to help improve the readability of the text.

Prusa's Slic3r did not need any infill because these features are all so small. I left it at the default 20%.

FreeCAD

FreeCad files are provided. The first version was a little inaccurate because of over-extrusion of the bottom layer making that ooze past the intended dimension. This version adds a chamfer to the bottom of the measuring edges to prevent that problem.

Each segment of the tool consists of a sketch extruded to the desired length. The text is an extruded shapetext printed as a void via Boolean cut. All segments are fused before exporting. If you wanted to make a custom tool that had just your favorite dimensions, you could dig in and copy them to a new document, then just set their X-axis positions (every 10mm) and re-fuse.

The typeface used is Trueno Bold, available under an open-font license at https://fontlibrary.org/en/font/trueno. I picked it because it was the first sans I saw there that looked like it might hold up at only 1.25mm height and had a "4" that is open at the top instead of closed... avoids one of the enclosed areas that will drop out when 3D printed as negative space (4, 6, 9, 0). Maybe some day I'll find a stencil-style typeface I like.

description.text: This fun weekend project with the kids started with a casual lunchtime inquiry about making a small playhouse for Hammy, my kids' hamster. This was created using our CO2 laser with a 12"x24" piece of 3mm birch plywood, and 3 scraps 3mm birch plywood.

The kids' diagram that inspired our build. We ended up a little smaller to conserve wood. Step 1 - Overall Design

I asked for a diagram of what they were hoping for, and then I used the Parametric Flexbox to create the overall outer shell. Although the kids wanted a larger playhouse, I wanted to create the walls all from one 12"x24" 3mm sheet of birch plywood and some scraps I had of the same 3mm plywood.

There is a screen capture of the settings I used in the Parametric Flexbox postscript file. For those not familiar with this process, the .ps file can be opened in Illustrator and it looks like a typical vector file. The wonderful thing about using this particular .ps file is that you can edit it in a text editor and change the parameters for the dimensions you want, including the radius of the rounded corners. Super Cool! Thanks to Brian Dahlen for making that tool!

Step 2 - Modifying the resulting PS file

The resulting vector file only gets you part way there... I added through cuts around the middle for a 2nd story floor, designed windows and a door, and created a roof that could lift off so my kids can tuck accessories inside for Hammy to climb on, or for cleaning. I designed around that 12"x24" piece of wood, which is a common size laser cutter bed for a lot of people. Three .AI files are included so you can jump right to this step if you like.

Step 3 - Laser cutting

Using the laser, I cut the wood with 'living hinges' to allow the walls to bend a smooth radius. This makes a great look and is fun to assemble with the kids.

The laser leaves a burn residue, which is probably better cleaned with denatured alcohol, but with a quality plywood, brief exposure to water is OK. The kids scrubbed away the burn marks for aesthetics, but also to make the house smell better to the hamster so she felt comfortable in there.

We dry fit the pieces while they were still wet and put them in the oven on 170F for about 20 minutes, which dried out the wood and helped set the desired bend of the living hinges.

Step 4 - Assembly

We used Aleene's Quick Dry Tacky Glue since it is quick with impatient kids, and it's non-toxic in case Hammy decided to sample a glue joint. Blue painter's tape held it all together while the glue dried.

When it was dry (less than an hour) I took it outside and gave it a light hand sanding to clean off the raised grain from getting it wet, and to further clean off the burn marks mainly on the hinge areas.

It currently has no finish, but I'm leaning toward a food grade mineral oil once I read up about how it might affect the hamster.

The video below shows Hammy's first impressions. There isn't any ladder to get to the second level yet, so it's just a blank slate for the kids to accessorize in the upcoming days.

description.text:
INTRODUCTION

Years ago when I first saw the Repeat-O-Meter, it seemed to me a very simple device that could be easily built. Why then did they retail for over fifteen hundred dollars, for such a simple device?

So, based on photographs of the actual device, and Tom Lipton's improvement of various features, I've produced my own version of this device which anyone with a basic shop shoulld be able to build.

I do not recommend 3D-printing this in plastic, I place this here anticipating a time when we will have cheap laser-sintering in various metal materials.

It also requires a basic indicator, and the brass-bushing which holds the indicator can be modified for any indicator mount size. There is currently a mock-up indicator shown in the model, for demonstration purposes.

PDF files for all screws required are included.

USAGE

The basic way that this device is used is on a flat surface plate, to find local dips or high-spots. Using this can tell you if you need to have your surface plate reground and recalibrated or not. No more guessing.

Zero out the RoM indicator on one spot, then run the device around on the surface plate and see if it records a positive or negative reading anywhere on the plate.

Also, for this tool to work at all, you will need to press-fit the balls into the bottom of the device and then surface grind them co-planar before you cut the center-flexure. And ideally, they should be lapped flat as well.

And you need a .0001" indicator.

This device is fairly arcane, but I had a good time designing it. Enjoy, and let me know if you find any use for it.

Details of the Design

There are a couple critical design aspects in this device.

The key is the flexure mechanism in the bottom center. I've spaced this .050" from the bottom, which allows that part to bend ever so slightly with the surface plate.

.050" may prove to be too much to get significant range of motion out of that flexure. In which case you have a couple options. Probably the easiest would be to simply surface grind the bottom of the part, taking off maybe .005" at a time until you get good motion.

You would have to knock the hardened feet out to do that, and the part has holes to allow you to press them out from above without problem. If you worried then that the hole would now be too big to get the feet to press back in, the solution is simple. Take a ball-peen hammer and lightly Brinel the metal all the way around each hole after removing the balls (hit hard enough to dent the metal), and this will cause the metal to displace into the hole, making it ever so slightly smaller, giving you enough metal to press into again later.

Another option would be to re-bore the flexure hole slightly larger, but this requires more tools and experience than just surface grinding the part.

Another option would be to add weight to that part of the foot, as it is the weight of the foot that causes the flexure to operate correctly. Another piece of steel on top, or even lead, would add significant weight to the tongue and cause it to flex more.

As for the angled support arms that seem to be constricting the tongue from moving, this is not the case. The screw is not tight on this part; there's a small amount of clearance both above and around it, using a bushing. This clearance allows the flexure to flex quite a bit, .025" in either direction, before the support-arm bottoms out and provides support.

This feature only exists to keep the device from being destroyed by overextending the flexure accidentally. With the support arms, the device is robust in a way that it could not be without them.

I have also thought about ways to create a part like this with other kinds of flexures. It might be possible to simplify the device quite a bit via other flexure designs. I will have to think about it.

Video of the device in action by the original designer:

description.text:
Two protective lens cap for a Aimpoint 5000 reddot sight. Caps will work for other sights with the same outer diamters.
SmallCap = for 30mm outer diameter opening.
BigCap = for 37mm outer diamter opening.

Tips and tricks.
If you are going to make your own, a few points I would concider is the fit, the hinge direction and thickness, and a possible lock.

  1. I made the cap diamter 0,4mm larger than needed, this made for a good fit.
  2. If the hinge is too thin the layers will break since they are all in the same direction. Make sure it's extra THICC.
  3. I used a "snap lock" at first, this relied on the plastic bending in order to operate. If you are to use this, keep in mind that the layer direction is important. Mine simply snapped off. I would recommend magnets instead.

title: Useless Box for Tower Pro Servo

description.text:
Edit 17/11/17: I have added an extremely bad wiring diagram to the images. Hopefully it's clear what I mean by it - let me know if it's not.

This is a remix of the Useless Machine by ericthepoolboy, modified to use the super common (eBay is full of them) Tower Pro SG90 micro servo. I modded the main box to fit the servo, then adjusted the activation arm as well. The only other changes I made from the original was the addition of some 'mouse ears' to the main box and moving lid. These 'ears' are easily removed after printing and help stop the corners lifting/warping on these parts. Worked great for me.
The activation arm could be a little prettier but it works well. I might revisit it at some point and dress it up a bit. I'm working on having a hand come out and flick the switch instead of a plain 'rod'.

I'm new to designing so any feedback is welcomed. Have a great day!

Thanks to ericthepoolboy for letting me use his design!

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

15%

Notes:

The only part that needs support is the activation arm.

The switch needs to be an on-on type (eBay to the rescue, just search on-on switch) and needs some slight adjustment as they're quite stiff. When you pull them apart, there is a little metal rod that goes up into the bit you 'flick'. Shorten that rod by a small amount (~2mm) and the switch gets much easier to move. If you take too much off the switch stops working so get a few just in case (I think I got 10 for like $3 shipped).
You will also need a micro switch (also called limit switch), again ebay to the rescue and they are super cheap. You only need one but I'd buy at least 10 as they're extremely useful things to have laying around.

comments.text:
Here's an ebay link to the type of switch I used - https://www.ebay.com.au/itm/DPDT-ON-ON-TOGGLE-SWITCH-Solder-6-PIN-2-Position-202-Car-Auto-12V-24V/181494144037?epid=686374957&hash=item2a41e4dc25:g:hCUAAOSwd4tT6r7i and another ebay link to the micro switch as well - https://www.ebay.com.au/itm/10Pcs-Micro-Roller-Lever-Arm-Open-Close-Limit-Switch-KW12-3-PCB-Microswitch-gau/182465064929?hash=item2a7bc3efe1:g:StoAAOSw5dNWiNTX .
To mount the arm to the servo I used one of the straight 'arms' that come with the servo and trimmed it to fit into the slot in the activation arm, then used the normal screw to screw it on to the servo.
To modify the servo itself, I took the 4 screws out of the bottom and lifted the top off, then cut the little plastic pin under one of the gears that stops it spinning all the way round (this may not even be necessary but is super easy). Then I ripped the wires out and soldered 2 wires directly to the motor, bypassing all the other electronics in there. Finally, I slightly enlarged the hole in the base of the servo where the wires exit, so the wires can come straight out the bottom instead of the side.
I'll try and get some more internal shots up in the next couple of days.

Since original cables of CR-10 were a bit short and I had some hassle when installing the printer in my wooden box I decided to change the cabling of the printer. Now it's a clean one cable solution and cables on printer are neatly installed.

Things you need:

  • 2x DB37 connectors (male & female)
  • Some cable
  • Some screws (spare screws from CR-10 will do the trick)
  • Printed connector box
  • 2x printed DB37 housing
  • Some patience when soldering all the wires :)

I've used an old printer cable for all the steppers and sensors. But for Bed an nozzle you have to use some thicker cables (I've used 1.5mm silicone cable). Also you have to pay attention that the sensors (bed and nozzle) ground is separated - else you will get false results when the fan blows. Tip: use some thicker cables for the ground pins as well (0.75mm).

I've attached a pin-out diagram of my printer as an idea on how to probably do it.

Please use this mod at your own risk. I don't take any responsibilities if your printer blows up or your house burns down. Be very careful when doing the cabling and soldering and apply propper isolation. Keep in mind the the power supply can deliver lots of current that can kill your wires immediately if they're too thin.

title: Killflash and sun shield for NcStar 3-12x56E

description.text:
This is a combination lens protector, killflash and sunvisor I designed for my NcStar 3-12x56E. The killflash insert pops into the sunshield from the back before it is placed on the scope.

The v5 "outsert" and the 8mm tall insert are the models I would suggest to print. The other inserts are not as effective at eliminating the scope glare, and may have potential to come loose if not glued into the sun shield. The other sun shield ("outsert") models will require some post-processing to fit the scope if the scaling is not perfect. The 8mm tall insert fits best, and has the honeycomb structure throughout the entire height of the model. It has 4mm holes with .48mm walls. I may revise this to .5mm, as it seems some slicers may not print walls these thin if you are using a .4mm nozzle.

The older honeycomb's holes are sized at 5.9mm (in order to allow as much light through as possible while still hopefully stopping airsoft BB's) with a .8mm wall between them.

The square grid pattern views clear, but if your retraction settings aren't perfect, it will have defects. The holes are 3mm with a .4mm wall between them. The square grid doesn't look as cool, but seems to print faster, and with its deeper walls and tighter spacing, seems to be more effective as a killflash. I might re-do or add another honeycomb pattern, later.

I designed this to use inserts so that they could be replaced if broken (as this is primarily for airsoft), if I wanted to change the design, and so that I could avoid having to print with supports.

The v2 "outsert" has very tight tolerances, so test a small portion of the print first to ensure it will fit. The v4 has slightly looser tolerances and a few other cosmetic changes.

v5, the version with the opening for a nut and screw has the loosest tolerances, and accepts a 4mm nut and hex screw to snug it up. I placed the nut and bolt on top, as with a 56mm aperture, this scope should be mounted as close to the bore as possible, and the added height of the nut and bolt for the sun shade would not help with that. This is the version I am recommending, as it should require less post-processing than the others.

title: Bosch GTA 6000 Stand Elevation with Caster Wheels
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a combined elevation and caster wheel foot for the Bosch GTA 6000 table saw stand.

The feet lift the stand by approximately 2 cm; that's what I needed to get the table saw on level with my workbench (yes, it's high;-).

To move the table saw around the foot incorporates a wheel with ball bearings. I think that the wheels would have worked without ball bearings too, but nothing to say agains a little overengineering, eh? ;-) You can see some ball bearing powered gliding action in this short video.

What you need
• print 4 feet "GTA 6000 Foot FINAL.stl"
• print 4 wheels "GTA 6000 Wheel FINAL.stl"
• 8 x 608 ball bearing (outer diameter 22mm, inner diameter 8mm, width 7mm)
• 4 x M8x60 DIN931 hex bolts
• 4 x M8 self-locking nuts

Assembly
Remove support material from feet and wheels. Glue ball bearings into wheels. Slide bolt through foot and wheel and tighten the nuts. Slide feet onto GTA 6000 stand. Lift up stand slightly, push and pull that thing across your workshop, enjoy! :-)
Concerning the bolt: An M8x60 machine bolt will be perfect. I had none at hand but an 8mm aluminum bolt. That's why I made my own axles. If you go this way the payload increases to bolt, metal saw, thread cutter, and cutting oil. This Die Guide may come in handy.

Acknowledgements
I had absolutely no clue about how to construct a tread with SketchUp so many thanks to Andreas for this great tutorial on Making Tires in SketchUp!

description.text:
My object is to have a toothbrush sized handle with a line of dental floss under tension to get right around all my dental nooks and crannies. The back molars are difficult to get to in my mouth and the dentist was giving me a hard time about not flossing properly.
The first model was made from a dinner fork with the middle prongs removed, the second was made of a similar sized aluminium strap bent into shape. Now I have a 3d printer I thought it would be fun to print one.
The challenge: To make an easily printable flosser, which takes a 5m spool of dental floss direct from its case; can unspool and lock as required; add tension to the other end of the dental floss with some ratchet type arrangement, and bingo - the Uberflossenthing
The flosser is super manoeuvrable and it is easy to get right round all the teeth and give 'em a good old flossing. I was using some Oral B floss which was good, and then changed to Colgate which has broken a few times. (When you find a thing that works.....)
Printing on my machine is with no support structure and the spools and spindles are printed vertically with the max amount of accuracy and strength available.
The ratchet on the waste spool locks very nicely and makes a very satisfying clicking sound.

Printer Brand:

Zortrax

Printer:

Zortrax M200

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Maximum

Notes:

I have attached the Freecad files as well, so you can play around with the design and size. Bigger or smaller may fit your teeth or your hand better.
The parts are designed to taper fit snugly, ( May need a light sanding depending on your machine) and be PUSHED apart when necessary. I've found that printed parts snap easily when under tension (eg bolts and screws) but that parts under compression are much stronger.
When you open a 5m case of floss, the spool inside is 12mm long and turns on an 8mm "axle". The printed spool spindle is designed to splay out when the parts are pressed together making a tight fit on the dental floss spool. Don't feel bad if you need to use a spot of super glue to stop the spool turning on the spindle. This project may test your printer's abilities. The backup is the dinner fork with the middle prongs removed and a couple of notches for the floss. I think that one is still my favourite.
A shout out to all the Freecad designers who continue to make an incredible software system absolutely free to anyone and everyone.

Extra Note
Following huge demand (n=1) I have added a small printer version if the basic flosser frame is too big for your printer. This has a hole in the frame for extra options re routing the dental floss. A flossed tooth is a happy tooth!

title: RoBo R1 E3D Sided Fan Duct

description.text:
A remix of a remix!
The common feedback with other remixes of this fan duct idea is that it directs too much air onto the hot end and causes some 'thermal runaway' errors and general heating problems. I have just added an aesthetical curve to each duct so air becomes directed either side of the hot end nozzle. This also means that both ducts don't just blow air into each other, in theory giving a better airflow cooling.

Above the duct is a ~12mm flat surface, this has been added so that I could stick a strip of LED lighting to the duct to further light up the print when the printer is used with Octoprint.
After printing I found the middle supports blocked air flow and it was worthwhile removing them.
I couldn't find the original CAD files, so the STL file was imported into Fusion 360 and edited.

title: Prusa i3 Fan Duct for J-Head & Wade - Improved Ver. 3

description.text: This is an improved variation of philsson's 40 mm fan duct. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:184055 There is now a bit more height at the two screw mounting slots. I improved the air flow in the duct again, by creating a transition between the main plenum and the ring duct. There should be even more air flowing to cool the extruded material now. I've also directed the flow of air around the nozzle a bit better. I had printed a few big herringbone gears for a Wade style extruder and they came out distorted. Turns out that most of the air flow that is directed at the extruded plastic was coming from one side. I've blocked some of the air flow in an attemped distribute it more evenly. It seems to work, the distortion problem stopped. The latest revision balances the exhaust to match the clockwise spin of most 40 mm cooling fans. I've tweeked the now 8 mm by 15 mm opening to help provide cooling air flow to the PEEK body of the J-Head. The theory is that it would reduce the chances of PLA jamming. It may also be beneficial for use with ABS, but I'm not using it with that kind of plastic at the moment. On the down side it might cool extruded ABS too much.

My wife had a work team building project that they needed to create something and I don't really know the specifics of it but they had a sketch of a Minion periscope they thought would work for their task. I thought 3d printing the whole thing would be difficult and well beyond my skillset. So I found a couple of things people already created and merged them together with Tinkercad.

These two prints were some of my longest prints and I'm not used to even checking out how much filament is left. So when I woke up in the morning it had already been printing without filament for a couple hours. Figuring the print was a lost cause, I switched to a black filament, located the layer it ran out at, manually edited the gcode, and restarted the print. Amazingly it worked out.

description.text:
Pattern Blocks: They are frequently used in K-5 math classes for students to explore shapes and their interconnections, make art projects, and build a foundation for other concepts such as fractions. While they are easy to design one by one, it is slightly challenging to get all of them from a hexagon (and eventually get to a 12-gon or even bigger structure). It is an interesting entry-point 3D design project for students to learn about sketching and constraints.

The all-in-one design fits a 140 x 140 platform; the square therein has a side length of 12mm and a thickness of 4mm. If you have a large bed, please scale up 200% for a regular set of pattern blocks.

The individual pieces are built with reference to a square that is 20mm x 20mm x 8mm. Have fun!
